What is a website cache?
Imagine a cafe:

You ordered a cappuccino first.
The barista made it from scratch — it's a long time.
Then the barista pre-made 10 more cappuccinos and put them on the counter.
They give it to the next customers ready — quickly.
This is the cache.:

origin server = “barista cooks from scratch"
cache/CDN = “ready copy on the counter”
How a regular query works
1) The first time
The user requests a file, for example /images/logo.png.

The cache looks at: “do I have a copy?”
No → this is a cache miss
Sends it to the main server.
The server returns a response.
The cache can save a copy.
2) The second time
Someone is asking for /images/logo.png again.

The cache already stores a copy → cache hit
Immediately gives away a copy without touching the main server.
Bottom line: faster and cheaper for the site.

Why is CDN important here
CDN is a lot of cache servers around the world.

You are in Kazakhstan → you receive a response from the nearest node.
A user in Germany → from a European node.
This way the site loads faster for everyone.

Where is the security issue (Web Cache Deception)
Now the important thing.

Sometimes the cache and the server understand URLs differently.

The cache thinks,
“Oh, the URL looks like a static file (.css, .js, .png) — it can be cached.”

And the server thinks:
“This is not a file, but a user's page. I'll give you my personal information.”

If an attacker picks up the URL, where:

the server will give you a personal page,
and the cache will save it as “regular static content”,
then another person can get this cached personal page.

This is the essence of web cache deception.

A very simple example
Let's say the victim has a personal page:

/account

The attacker tries a “tricky” URL:

/account/something.css

What can happen with vulnerability:

The victim (logged into the account) opens this link.
The server returns her /account page with personal data anyway.
The cache sees it .css thinks “static file, cached".
The attacker opens the same URL and receives an already cached copy with the victim's data.
Why is this happening
Because there is a logic out of sync:

cache logic (what is considered “cacheable”),
application logic (what content is actually returned).
If these rules are not agreed upon, a hole appears.

How to defend yourself (without difficulties)
Never cache personal responses

For personal pages: Cache-Control: no-store (or at least private).
Strict routing

/account should only work as /account.
/account/anything.css should not return personal data.
Common rules between CDN and backend

So that both understand URLs and caching equally.
Do not cache responses with cookies/authorization

Especially if there is a Set Cookie, personal data, profile, shopping cart, etc.



How to construct a web cache deception attack 
1) Find a sensitive dynamic endpoint
Look for pages that return user-specific data, such as:

/my-account
/profile
/orders
Check the raw HTTP response in Burp, not just what you see in the browser UI.

2) Use cacheable request methods
Start with methods that are commonly cached:

GET
HEAD
OPTIONS
(POST is usually not cached.)

3) Find a parsing mismatch (cache vs origin)
You need a URL that the origin and the cache interpret differently.

Common mismatch types:

URL-to-resource mapping mismatch
Origin treats /profile/anything as /profile, but cache treats it as a separate static resource.

Delimiter handling mismatch
One side ignores special characters like ;, encoded slashes, etc., while the other side does not.

Path normalization mismatch
Differences in handling //, /./, /../, %2f, %2e, etc.

4) Craft a malicious URL
Goal: make origin return sensitive dynamic content, while cache thinks it is static and stores it.

Typical patterns to test:

/my-account/nonexistent.css
/profile;test.css
/profile/%2e%2e/profile.css
(Exact payload depends on the app behavior.)

5) Cache the victim’s response
If a logged-in victim requests that malicious URL, their personalized response may be cached.

6) Request the same URL yourself
Send the same request from Burp Repeater and check whether you get cached victim data.

Use Burp (not just browser) to avoid:

auto-redirect confusion,
session side effects,
hidden response differences.
What to check in responses
Cache-Control
Age (increasing value suggests cached response)
X-Cache (HIT / MISS)
CDN-specific headers (for example CF-Cache-Status)
Same response body returned to different sessions/users
One-line summary
A web cache deception attack works when the origin serves private dynamic content, but the cache mistakenly stores it as public cacheable content.

How to detect cached responses (quick workflow)
Send a request once.
Send the exact same request again.
Compare:
headers (X-Cache, Age, Cache-Control, CDN headers),
response time.
If second response is faster and headers show cache indicators, it is likely cached.

Key headers and what they mean
X-Cache: hit
Response came from cache.

X-Cache: miss
Not in cache yet; fetched from origin.
Send same request again to see if it becomes hit.

X-Cache: dynamic
Origin generated dynamic content; usually not cached.

X-Cache: refresh
Cached object existed but was stale, so cache revalidated/refreshed it.

Cache-Control: public, max-age=...
Resource is intended to be cacheable.
Important: this is a hint, not proof of an actual cache hit.

Time-based signal
If request #1 is slow and request #2 is much faster (same request, same conditions), that often means:

first = origin fetch,
second = cache hit.
Useful extra headers to watch
Age (higher value strongly suggests cached object age)
CF-Cache-Status (Cloudflare: HIT, MISS, BYPASS, DYNAMIC)
Via / X-Served-By (often indicates proxy/cache layer)
Common testing mistakes
Changing the request accidentally (different cookie/query/header = different cache key).
Trusting only Cache-Control without verifying with repeated requests.
Testing only in browser (redirects/session behavior can hide cache behavior).
